SIMPLE: dishevel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dishevel
<hw>Di*shev"el</hw> <pr>(d⟦icr⟧*sh⟦ecr⟧v"'l <it>or</it> -⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Disheveled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Dishevelled</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Disheveling</conjf> or
<conjf>Dishevelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>descheveler</ets>,
F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧cheveler</ets>, LL. <ets>discapillare</ets>;
<ets>dis-</ets> + L. <ets>capillus</ets> the hair of the head. See
<er>Capillary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To suffer (the hair) to hang
loosely or disorderly; to spread or throw (the hair) in disorder; --
used chiefly in the passive participle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With garments rent and hair <qex>disheveled</qex>,⟦br⟧
Wringing her hands and making piteous moan.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spread loosely or disorderly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like the fair flower <qex>disheveled</qex> in the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dishevel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dishevel
<hw>Di*shev"el</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be spread in disorder or
hang negligently, as the hair.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dishevele</ent>⟦br⟧
